treasure, by the way,

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:40.490 align:middle line:84%
so the treasure literally goes
back to the concept of a book.

00:38:40.490 --> 00:38:42.240 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't a monetary
treasure because when

00:38:42.240 --> 00:38:44.890 align:middle line:84%
you think about the etymology
of treasure, "tresaurus,"

00:38:44.890 --> 00:38:47.250 align:middle line:84%
it literally is a
treasure of words,

00:38:47.250 --> 00:38:49.500 align:middle line:84%
because that's where we get
the word "thesaurus" from.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:51.291 align:middle line:84%
So when you are thinking
about the Templars

00:38:51.291 --> 00:38:53.120 align:middle line:84%
looking for a treasure
on the Temple Mount,

00:38:53.120 --> 00:38:55.050 align:middle line:84%
yeah, if you're into
monetary things, yeah,

00:38:55.050 --> 00:38:57.000 align:middle line:84%
that makes a lot
of sense, but not

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:59.040 align:middle line:84%
if you're into
spiritual degrees, which

00:38:59.040 --> 00:39:01.770 align:middle line:84%
is what the inner Templar
brotherhood was doing.

00:39:01.770 --> 00:39:04.440 align:middle line:84%
The original concept
of treasure was a book.

00:39:04.440 --> 00:39:06.240 align:middle line:84%
And the book, literally
the [NON-ENGLISH],,

00:39:06.240 --> 00:39:08.580 align:middle line:90%
it means "treasure" in Mandaean.

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:10.230 align:middle line:84%
And that book is
the Book of John

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:12.974 align:middle line:84%
the Baptist, which the church
says never was written,

00:39:12.974 --> 00:39:15.640 align:middle line:84%
which makes, of course, the book
